05397nam a22007335i 9780292793101DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212010txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927931017 a10.7560/7218832doi  a(DE-B1597)588147  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aKFT1601.6.S55bL39 2010eb 7aHIS0361302bisacsh04a342.76408/722204aThe Laws of Slavery in Texas :bHistorical Documents and Essays /ced. by Randolph B. Campbell, Marilyn P. Duncan, William S. Pugsley. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2010  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tProject Director’s Foreword -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Editorial Style -- tIntroduction. Human Chattels: Th e Laws of Slavery in Texas -- t1. Laws on Slavery in Mexican Texas, 1821–1836 -- tLegal Documents -- tArticles -- t2. Laws on Slavery in the Republic and Statehood Periods, 1836–1860 -- tLegal Documents -- tArticles -- tCases -- t3. Laws on Free Negroes in the Republic and Statehood Periods, 1836–1860 -- tLegal Documents -- tArticle -- tCase -- t4. Laws on Slavery and Freedom in Confederate and Reconstruction Texas, 1861–1874 -- tLegal Document -- tArticle -- tCases -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe laws that governed the institution of slavery in early Texas were enacted over a fifty-year period in which Texas moved through incarnations as a Spanish colony, a Mexican state, an independent republic, a part of the United States, and a Confederate state. This unusual legal heritage sets Texas apart from the other slave-holding states and provides a unique opportunity to examine how slave laws were enacted and upheld as political and legal structures changed. The Laws of Slavery in Texas makes that examination possible by combining seminal historical essays with excerpts from key legal documents from the slave period and tying them together with interpretive commentary by the foremost scholar on the subject, Randolph B. Campbell. Campbell's commentary focuses on an aspect of slave law that was particularly evident in the evolving legal system of early Texas: the dilemma that arose when human beings were treated as property. As Campbell points out, defining slaves as moveable property, or chattel, presented a serious difficulty to those who wrote and interpreted the law because, unlike any other form of property, slaves were sentient beings. They were held responsible for their crimes, and in numerous other ways statute and case law dealing with slavery recognized the humanness of the enslaved. Attempts to protect the property rights of slave owners led to increasingly restrictive laws—including laws concerning free blacks—that were difficult to uphold. The documents in this collection reveal both the roots of the dilemma and its inevitable outcome.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansxLegal status, laws, etc.zTexasxHistory. 0aSlaveryxLaw and legislationzTexasxHistory. 0aSlavesxEmancipationzTexas. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / Southwest (AZ, NM, OK, TX).2bisacsh1 aBugbee, Lester G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Randolph B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Randolph B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavidson, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuncan, Marilyn P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGreenhill, Joe R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeir Nash, A. E., 